&nbsp;
- THE FINANCIAL QATAR TV Al Jazeera was founded in Doha in 1996 by a decree issued by the former emiro of Qatar, Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani. While establishing that the channel should be "totally independent of every influence", the decree also provided a government loan of $150 million for "its creation and cover of operating costs for five years". Although Al Jazeera Media Network is a private company, the broadcaster has maintained some funding from the Qatar government, which its critics often cite when questioning its publishing independence from Doha. The broadcaster immediately emerged as a rival of international media giants, but his cover without exclusion of blows as a self-defined "first independent news channel in the Arab world" also unleashed a series of legal disputes in the region in his early years.
&nbsp;
- TV 'GLOBAL &nbsp; PRESENT IN QUASI 100 COUNTRIES The channel claims to operate in 95 countries with 70 offices and a staff of 3,000 employees, with a global audience of 430 million homes. At Jazeera, the first Arabic news channel of the network, was joined in 2006 by a service in English. At Jazeera and Al Jazeera English - the top channels of the network - have separate editorial lines with the Arabic language channel that most often faces criticism from the inside of the region. The network also includes a live public business channel, Al Jazeera Mubasher, and its only digital AJ+ channel, aimed at a youth audience.
&nbsp;
-&nbsp; THE VOICE OF THE ARABE&nbsp; When a wave of popular uprisings overwhelmed the Middle East and North Africa in 2011, Al Jazeera was seen as a key factor in shaping public opinion because it granted an unprecedented transmission space to opposition groups, especially the Muslim Brotherhood. The network has repeatedly rejected any partiality charge in its coverage. Al Jazeera had to face pressure from governments across the region and became the core of the feud between Cairo and Doha after the military assassination of the Egyptian President of the Muslim Brotherhood Mohamed Morsi in 2013. Cairo considered him a spokesman for the Islamist movement of Morsi and the Egyptian authorities arrested three journalists of Al Jazeera, including Australian Peter Greste, provoking international condemnation.
&nbsp;
_ In 2017, Qatar's neighbors, led by Saudi Arabia, imposed a three-year diplomatic and economic blockade to the Gulf monarchy. In addition to asking Qatar to cut ties with the Muslim Brotherhood and its sister organization Hamas, and to reduce relations with Iran, the boycott states also called for the closure of Al Jazeera and all its affiliates. The channel called pressures an attempt to "put freedom of expression". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
- THE COPERTURE OF GUERRA DI GAZA AND THE IRA DI NETANYAHU From the beginning of the war in Gaza on October 7, Al Jazeera has transmitted continuous reports on the field of the Israeli campaign and its consequences. His broadcasts were among the most followed in the Middle East, despite the widespread disincanto against Western media coverage. Last month Netanyahu called Al Jazeera a "terroristic channel", saying that he would "act immediately" to stop his activities after the approval of a new law. At the time, the broadcaster called the ban "part of a series of Israeli systematic attacks to silence Al Jazeera", which according to Arabic TV included the killing of Shireen Abu Akleh, one of the most important journalists in the region, while covering an Israeli raid in the West Bank occupied in May 2022.
&nbsp;
From the beginning of the war in Gaza, Al Jazeera's office in the Palestinian territory was bombed and two of his correspondents were killed. In January, Israel said that a journalist from Al Jazeera's staff and a freelancer killed in an air strike in Gaza were "terroristic agents". The following month he accused another journalist of the canal, wounded in a separate strike, of being a "vice commander of company" of Hamas. At Jazeera he fiercely denied the accusations of Israel and accused him of systematically targeting Al Jazeera's employees in the Gaza Strip. His head of office in Gaza, Wael al-Dahdouh, was wounded in an Israeli attack in December that killed the cameraman on the network. His wife, two of their sons and a grandson were killed in the October bombing of the Nuseirat refugee camp in central Gaza. His eldest son was Al Jazeera's journalist killed in January when a strike targeted a car at Rafah.&nbsp;

